Basic IT Help Desk Troubleshooting (Short Version)

Core Methodology

    Gather Information: Ask what happened, when, where, and to whom. Try to reproduce the issue.
    Identify Scope: Determine if it affects one user, one device, or multiple systems.
    Check the Obvious First: Power, cables, network connections, login credentials, recent updates or changes.
    Isolate the Variable: Change or test one thing at a time to find the root cause.
    Document Everything: Record steps taken, results, and the final resolution.

Universal Quick Fixes

    Restart the device (resolves a large portion of common issues)
    Check network connectivity: toggle Wi‑Fi, reseat Ethernet, ping gateway/DNS
    Verify user permissions: account lockout, password expiry, MFA prompts
    Clear browser cache/cookies or test in incognito/private mode
    Update, repair, or reinstall the affected application

Common Scenarios & First Actions

    Can't log in: Confirm caps lock/num lock, reset password, check for account lockout or domain sync issues
    No internet: Ping local gateway → DNS server → external IP; verify proxy/VPN settings
    Printer issues: Set as default printer, clear print spooler service, reinstall or update driver
    Slow performance: Review Task Manager/Activity Monitor, check disk space, pause pending updates
    App crashes: Run as administrator, try compatibility mode, check Event Viewer or system logs for errors

Pro Tips

    Apply the OSI model mentally: start at Layer 1 (physical/cables) and move up to Layer 7 (application)
    Master key command-line tools: ipconfig/ifconfig, ping, nslookup, tracert, sfc /scannow
    Use remote support tools efficiently: screen share, remote desktop, remote PowerShell/SSH
    Escalate with context: include error messages, steps already tried, and user impact
    Practice clear communication: confirm understanding, avoid unexplained jargon, verify resolution with the user

    Golden Rule: If it isn't documented, it didn't happen.
